\mt1 JEREMIAH. 
\c 1  
\m
\v 1  \sc The\sc* words of Jeremiah the son of Hilkiah, of the priests that \add were\add* in Anathoth in the land of Benjamin: 
\v 2 to whom the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came in the days of Josiah the son of Amon king of Judah, in the thirteenth year of his reign. 
\v 3 It came also in the days of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah king of Judah, unto the end of the eleventh year of Zedekiah the son of Josiah king of Judah, unto the carrying away of Jerusalem captive in the fifth month. 
\p
\v 4 Then the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me, saying, 
\v 5 Before I formed thee in the belly I knew thee; and before thou camest forth out of the womb I sanctified thee, \add and\add* I ordained thee a prophet unto the nations. 
\v 6 Then said I, Ah, Lord \sc God\sc*, behold, I cannot speak: for I \add am\add* a child. 
\v 7 But the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, Say not, I \add am\add* a child: for thou shalt go to all that I shall send thee, and whatsoever I command thee thou shalt speak. 
\v 8 Be not afraid of their faces: for I \add am\add* with thee to deliver thee, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 9 Then the \sc Lord\sc* put forth his hand, and touched my mouth. And the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, Behold, I have put my words in thy mouth. 
\v 10 See, I have this day set thee over the nations and over the kingdoms, to root out, and to pull down, and to destroy, and to throw down, to build, and to plant. 
\p
\v 11 Moreover, the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me, saying, Jeremiah, what seest thou? And I said, I see a rod of an almond tree. 
\v 12 Then said the \sc Lord\sc* unto me, Thou hast well seen: for I will hasten my word to perform it. 
\v 13 And the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me the second time, saying, What seest thou? And I said, I see a seething pot; and the face thereof \add is\add* towards the north. 
\v 14 Then the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, Out of the north an evil shall break forth upon all the inhabitants of the land. 
\v 15 For lo, I will call all the families of the kingdoms of the north, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; and they shall come, and they shall set every one his throne \add at\add* the entering of the gates of Jerusalem, and against all the walls thereof round about, and against all the cities of Judah. 
\v 16 And I will utter my judgments against them touching all their wickedness, who have forsaken me, and have burnt incense unto other gods, and worshipped the works of their own hands. 
\v 17 Thou therefore gird up thy loins, and arise, and speak unto them all that I command thee: be not dismayed at their faces, lest I confound thee before them. 
\v 18 For behold, I have made thee \add this\add* day a defenced city, and an iron pillar, and brasen walls against the whole land, against the kings of Judah, against the princes thereof, against the priests thereof, and against the people of the land. 
\v 19 And they shall fight against thee; but they shall not prevail against thee; for I \add am\add* with thee, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, to deliver thee. 
\c 2  
\p
\v 1 Moreover the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came to me, saying, 
\v 2 Go and cry in the ears of Jerusalem, saying, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; I remember thee, the kindness of thy youth, the love of thine espousals, when thou wentest after me in the wilderness, in a land \add that was\add* not sown. 
\v 3 Israel \add was\add* holiness unto the \sc Lord\sc*, \add and\add* the firstfruits of his increase: all that devour him shall offend; evil shall come upon them, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 4 Hear ye the word of the \sc Lord\sc*, O house of Jacob, and all the families of the house of Israel: 
\v 5 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, What iniquity have your fathers found in me, that they are gone far from me, and have walked after vanity, and are become vain? 
\v 6 Neither said they, Where \add is\add* the \sc Lord\sc* that brought us up out of the land of Egypt, that led us through the wilderness, through a land of deserts and of pits, through a land of drought, and of the shadow of death, through a land that no man passed through, and where no man dwelt? 
\v 7 And I brought you into a plentiful country, to eat the fruit thereof and the goodness thereof; but when ye entered, ye defiled my land, and made mine heritage an abomination. 
\v 8 The priests said not, Where \add is\add* the \sc Lord\sc*? and they that handle the law knew me not: the pastors also transgressed against me, and the prophets prophesied by Baal, and walked after \add things that\add* do not profit. 
\v 9 Wherefore I will yet plead with you, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and with your children’s children will I plead. 
\v 10 For pass over the isles of Chittim, and see; and send \add unto\add* Kedar, and consider diligently, and see if there be such a \add thing\add*. 
\v 11 Hath a nation changed \add their\add* gods, which \add are\add* yet no gods? but my people have changed their glory for \add that which\add* doth not profit. 
\v 12 Be astonished, O ye heavens, at this, and be horribly afraid, be ye very desolate, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 13 For my people have committed two evils; they have forsaken me the fountain of living waters, and hewed them out cisterns, broken cisterns, that can hold no water. 
\p
\v 14  \add Is\add* Israel a servant? \add is\add* he a homeborn \add slave?\add* why is he spoiled? 
\v 15 The young lions roared upon him, \add and\add* yelled, and they made his land waste: his cities are burnt without inhabitant. 
\v 16 Also the children of Noph and Tahapanes have broken the crown of thy head. 
\v 17 Hast thou not procured this unto thyself, in that thou hast forsaken the \sc Lord\sc* thy God, when he led thee by the way? 
\v 18 And now what hast thou to do in the way of Egypt, to drink the waters of Sihor? or what hast thou to do in the way of Assyria, to drink the waters of the river? 
\v 19 Thine own wickedness shall correct thee, and thy backslidings shall reprove thee: know therefore and see that \add it is\add* an evil \add thing\add* and bitter, that thou hast forsaken the \sc Lord\sc* thy God, and \add that\add* my fear \add is\add* not in thee, saith the Lord \sc God\sc* of hosts. 
\v 20 For of old time I have broken thy yoke, \add and\add* burst thy bands; and thou saidst, I will not transgress; when upon every high hill and under every green tree thou wanderest, playing the harlot. 
\v 21 Yet I had planted thee a noble vine, wholly a right seed: how then art thou turned \add into\add* the degenerate plant of a strange vine unto me? 
\v 22 For though thou wash thee with nitre, and take thee much sope, \add yet\add* thine iniquity \add is\add* marked before me, saith the Lord \sc God\sc*. 
\v 23 How canst thou say, I am not polluted, I have not gone after Baalim? see thy way in the valley, know what thou hast done: \add thou art\add* a swift dromedary traversing her ways; 
\v 24 a wild ass used to the wilderness, \add that\add* snuffeth up the wind at her pleasure; \add in\add* her occasion who can turn her away? all they that seek her will not weary themselves; in her month they shall find her. 
\v 25 Withhold thy foot from being unshod, and thy throat from thirst: but thou saidst, There is no hope: no; for I have loved strangers, and after them will I go. 
\v 26 As the thief is ashamed when he is found, so is the house of Israel ashamed; they, their kings, their princes, and their priests, and their prophets, 
\v 27 saying to a stock, Thou \add art\add* my father; and to a stone, Thou hast brought me forth: for they have turned \add their\add* back unto me, and not \add their\add* face: but in the time of their trouble they will say, Arise, and save us. 
\v 28 But where \add are\add* thy gods that thou hast made thee? let them arise, if they can save thee in the time of thy trouble: for \add according\add* to the number of thy cities are thy gods, O Judah. 
\v 29 Wherefore will ye plead with me? ye all have transgressed against me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 30 In vain have I smitten your children; they received no correction: your own sword hath devoured your prophets, like a destroying lion. 
\p
\v 31 O generation, see ye the word of the \sc Lord\sc*. Have I been a wilderness unto Israel? a land of darkness? wherefore say my people, We are lords; we will come no more unto thee? 
\v 32 Can a maid forget her ornaments, \add or\add* a bride her attire? yet my people have forgotten me days without number. 
\v 33 Why trimmest thou thy way to seek love? therefore hast thou also taught the wicked ones thy ways. 
\v 34 Also in thy skirts is found the blood of the souls of the poor innocents: I have not found it by secret search, but upon all these. 
\v 35 Yet thou sayest, Because I am innocent, surely his anger shall turn from me. Behold, I \add will\add* plead with thee, because thou sayest, I have not sinned. 
\v 36 Why gaddest thou about \add so\add* much to change thy way? thou also shalt be ashamed of Egypt, as thou wast ashamed of Assyria. 
\v 37 Yea, thou shalt go forth from him, and thine hands upon thine head: for the \sc Lord\sc* hath rejected thy confidences, and thou shalt not prosper in them. 
\c 3  
\p
\v 1 They say, If a man put away his wife, and she go from him, and become another man’s, shall he return unto her again? shall not that land be greatly polluted? but thou hast played the harlot with many lovers; yet return again to me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 2 Lift up thine eyes unto the high places, and see where thou hast not been lien with. In the ways hast thou sat for them, as the Arabian in the wilderness; and thou hast polluted the land with thy whoredoms and with thy wickedness. 
\v 3 Therefore the showers have been withholden, and there hath been no latter rain; and thou hadst a whore’s forehead, thou refusedst to be ashamed. 
\v 4 Wilt thou not from this time cry unto me, My father, thou \add art\add* the guide of my youth? 
\v 5 Will he reserve \add his anger\add* for ever? will he keep \add it\add* to the end? Behold, thou hast spoken and done evil \add things\add* as thou couldest. 
\p
\v 6 The \sc Lord\sc* said also unto me in the days of Josiah the king, Hast thou seen \add that\add* which backsliding Israel hath done? she is gone up upon every high mountain and under every green tree, and there hath played the harlot. 
\v 7 And I said after she had done all these \add things\add*, Turn thou unto me. But she returned not. And her treacherous sister Judah saw \add it\add*. 
\v 8 And I saw, when for all the causes whereby backsliding Israel committed adultery I had put her away, and given her a bill of divorce; yet her treacherous sister Judah feared not, but went and played the harlot also. 
\v 9 And it came to pass through the lightness of her whoredom, that she defiled the land, and committed adultery with stones and with stocks. 
\v 10 And yet for all this her treacherous sister Judah hath not turned unto me with her whole heart, but feignedly, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 11 And the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, The backsliding Israel hath justified herself more than treacherous Judah. 
\v 12 Go and proclaim these words toward the north, and say, Return, thou backsliding Israel, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; \add and\add* I will not cause mine anger to fall upon you: for I \add am\add* merciful, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, \add and\add* I will not keep \add anger\add* for ever. 
\v 13 Only acknowledge thine iniquity, that thou hast transgressed against the \sc Lord\sc* thy God, and hast scattered thy ways to the strangers under every green tree, and ye have not obeyed my voice, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 14 Turn, O backsliding children, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; for I am married unto you: and I will take you one of a city, and two of a family, and I will bring you \add to\add* Zion: 
\v 15 and I will give you pastors according to mine heart, which shall feed you with knowledge and understanding. 
\v 16 And it shall come to pass, when ye be multiplied and increased in the land, in those days, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, they shall say no more, The ark of the covenant of the \sc Lord\sc*: neither shall it come to mind: neither shall they remember it; neither shall they visit \add it;\add* neither shall \add that\add* be done any more. 
\v 17 At that time they shall call Jerusalem the throne of the \sc Lord\sc*; and all the nations shall be gathered unto it, to the name of the \sc Lord\sc*, to Jerusalem: neither shall they walk any more after the imagination of their evil heart. 
\v 18 In those days the house of Judah shall walk with the house of Israel, and they shall come together out of the land of the north to the land that I have given for an inheritance unto your fathers. 
\v 19 But I said, How shall I put thee among the children, and give thee a pleasant land, a goodly heritage of the hosts of nations? and I said, Thou shalt call me, My father; and shalt not turn away from me. 
\v 20 Surely \add as\add* a wife treacherously departeth from her husband, so have you dealt treacherously with me, O house of Israel, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\p
\v 21 A voice was heard upon the high places, weeping \add and\add* supplications of the children of Israel: for they have perverted their way, \add and\add* they have forgotten the \sc Lord\sc* their God. 
\v 22 Return, ye backsliding children, \add and\add* I will heal your backslidings. Behold, we come unto thee; for thou \add art\add* the \sc Lord\sc* our God. 
\v 23 Truly in vain \add is salvation hoped for\add* from the hills, \add and from\add* the multitude of mountains: truly in the \sc Lord\sc* our God \add is\add* the salvation of Israel. 
\v 24 For shame hath devoured the labour of our fathers from our youth; their flocks and their herds, their sons and their daughters. 
\v 25 We lie down in our shame, and our confusion covereth us: for we have sinned against the \sc Lord\sc* our God, we and our fathers, from our youth even unto this day, and have not obeyed the voice of the \sc Lord\sc* our God. 
\c 4  
\p
\v 1 If thou wilt return, O Israel, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, return unto me: and if thou wilt put away thine abominations out of my sight, then shalt thou not remove. 
\v 2 And thou shalt swear, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth, in truth, in judgment, and in righteousness; and the nations shall bless themselves in him, and in him shall they glory. 
\v 3 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* to the men of Judah and Jerusalem, Break up your fallow ground, and sow not among thorns. 
\v 4 Circumcise yourselves to the \sc Lord\sc*, and take away the foreskins of your heart, ye men of Judah and inhabitants of Jerusalem: lest my fury come forth like fire, and burn that none can quench \add it\add*, because of the evil of your doings. 
\v 5 Declare ye in Judah, and publish in Jerusalem; and say, Blow ye the trumpet in the land: cry, gather together, and say, Assemble yourselves, and let us go into the defenced cities. 
\v 6 Set up the standard toward Zion: retire, stay not: for I will bring evil from the north, and a great destruction. 
\v 7 The lion is come up from his thicket, and the destroyer of the Gentiles is on his way; he is gone forth from his place to make thy land desolate; \add and\add* thy cities shall be laid waste, without an inhabitant. 
\v 8 For this gird you with sackcloth, lament and howl: for the fierce anger of the \sc Lord\sc* is not turned back from us. 
\v 9 And it shall come to pass at that day, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, \add that\add* the heart of the king shall perish, and the heart of the princes; and the priests shall be astonished, and the prophets shall wonder. 
\v 10 (Then said I, Ah, Lord \sc God\sc*! surely thou hast greatly deceived this people and Jerusalem, saying, Ye shall have peace; whereas the sword reacheth unto the soul). 
