\p
\v 1 Righteous \add art\add* thou, O \sc Lord\sc*, when I plead with thee: yet let me talk with thee of \add thy\add* judgments. Wherefore doth the way of the wicked prosper? \add wherefore\add* are all they happy that deal very treacherously? 
\v 2 Thou hast planted them, yea, they have taken root: they grow, yea, they bring forth fruit: thou \add art\add* near in their mouth, and far from their reins. 
\v 3 But thou, O \sc Lord\sc*, knowest me: thou hast seen me, and tried mine heart towards thee: pull them out like sheep for the slaughter, and prepare them for the day of slaughter. 
\v 4 How long shall the land mourn, and the herbs of every field wither, for the wickedness of them that dwell therein? the beasts are consumed, and the birds; because they said, He shall not see our last end. 
\p
\v 5 If thou hast run with the footmen, and they have wearied thee, then how canst thou contend with horses? and \add if\add* in the land of peace, \add wherein\add* thou trustedst, \add they wearied thee\add*, then how wilt thou do in the swelling of Jordan? 
\v 6 For even thy brethren, and the house of thy father, even they have dealt treacherously with thee; yea, they have called a multitude after thee: believe them not, though they speak fair \add words\add* unto thee. 
\p
\v 7 I have forsaken mine house, I have left mine heritage; I have given the dearly beloved of my soul into the hand of her enemies. 
\v 8 Mine heritage is unto me as a lion in the forest; it crieth out against me: therefore have I hated it. 
\v 9 Mine heritage \add is\add* unto me \add as\add* a speckled bird, the birds round about \add are\add* against her; come ye, assemble all the beasts of the field, come to devour. 
\v 10 Many pastors have destroyed my vineyard, they have trodden my portion under foot, they have made my pleasant portion a desolate wilderness. 
\v 11 They have made it desolate, \add and being\add* desolate it mourneth unto me; the whole land is made desolate, because no man layeth \add it\add* to heart. 
\v 12 The spoilers are come upon all high places through the wilderness: for the sword of the \sc Lord\sc* \add shall\add* devour from the \add one\add* end of the land even to the \add other\add* end of the land: no flesh \add shall\add* have peace. 
\v 13 They have sown wheat, but shall reap thorns: they have put themselves to pain, \add but\add* shall not profit: and they shall be ashamed of your revenues because of the fierce anger of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\p
\v 14 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* against all mine evil neighbours, that touch the inheritance which I have caused my people Israel to inherit; Behold, I will pluck them out of their land, and pluck out the house of Judah from among them. 
\v 15 And it shall come to pass, after that I have plucked them out, I will return, and have compassion on them, and will bring them again, every man to his heritage, and every man to his land. 
\v 16 And it shall come to pass, if they will diligently learn the ways of my people, to swear by my name, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth; as they taught my people to swear by Baal; then shall they be built in the midst of my people. 
\v 17 But if they will not obey, I will utterly pluck up and destroy that nation, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\c 13  
\p
\v 1 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* unto me, Go and get thee a linen girdle, and put it upon thy loins, and put it not in water. 
\v 2 So I got a girdle, according to the word of the \sc Lord\sc*, and put \add it\add* on my loins. 
\v 3 And the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me the second time, saying, 
\v 4 Take the girdle that thou hast got, which \add is\add* upon thy loins, and arise, go to Euphrates, and hide it there in a hole of the rock. 
\v 5 So I went, and hid it by Euphrates, as the \sc Lord\sc* commanded me. 
\v 6 And it came to pass after many days, that the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, Arise, go to Euphrates, and take the girdle from thence, which I commanded thee to hide there. 
\v 7 Then I went to Euphrates, and digged, and took the girdle from the place where I had hid it: and behold, the girdle was marred, it was profitable for nothing. 
\v 8 Then the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me, saying, 
\v 9 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, After this manner will I mar the pride of Judah, and the great pride of Jerusalem. 
\v 10 This evil people, which refuse to hear my words, which walk in the imagination of their heart, and walk after other gods, to serve them, and to worship them, shall even be as this girdle, which is good for nothing. 
\v 11 For as the girdle cleaveth to the loins of a man, so have I caused to cleave unto me the whole house of Israel and the whole house of Judah, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; that \add they\add* might be unto me for a people, and for a name, and for a praise, and for a glory: but they would not hear. 
\p
\v 12 Therefore thou shalt speak unto them this word; Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* God of Israel, Every bottle shall be filled \add with\add* wine: and they shall say unto thee, Do we not certainly know that every bottle shall be filled \add with\add* wine? 
\v 13 Then shalt thou say unto them, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, Behold, I \add will\add* fill all the inhabitants of this land, even the kings that sit upon David’s throne, and the priests, and the prophets, and all the inhabitants of Jerusalem, \add with\add* drunkenness. 
\v 14 And I will dash them one against another, even the fathers and the sons together, saith the \sc Lord\sc*: I will not pity, nor spare, nor have mercy, but destroy them. 
\p
\v 15 Hear ye, and give ear; be not proud: for the \sc Lord\sc* hath spoken. 
\v 16 Give glory to the \sc Lord\sc* your God, before he cause darkness, and before your feet stumble upon the dark mountains, and, while ye look for light, he turn it into the shadow of death, \add and\add* make \add it\add* gross darkness. 
\v 17 But if ye will not hear it, my soul shall weep in secret places for \add your\add* pride; and mine eye shall weep sore, and run down \add with\add* tears, because the \sc Lord’s\sc* flock is carried away captive. 
\v 18 Say unto the king and to the queen, Humble yourselves, sit down: for your principalities shall come down, \add even\add* the crown of your glory. 
\v 19 The cities of the south shall be shut up, and none shall open \add them:\add* Judah shall be carried away captive all of it, it shall be wholly carried away captive. 
\v 20 Lift up your eyes, and behold them that come from the north: where \add is\add* the flock \add that\add* was given thee, thy beautiful flock? 
\v 21 What wilt thou say when he shall punish thee? for thou hast taught them \add to be\add* captains, \add and\add* as chief over thee: shall not sorrows take thee, as a woman in travail? 
\v 22 And if thou say in thine heart, Wherefore come these \add things\add* upon me? For the greatness of thine iniquity are thy skirts discovered, \add and\add* thy heels made bare. 
\v 23 Can the Ethiopian change his skin, or the leopard his spots? \add then\add* may ye also do good, that are accustomed to do evil. 
\v 24 Therefore will I scatter them as the stubble that passeth away by the wind of the wilderness. 
\v 25 This \add is\add* thy lot, the portion of thy measures from me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; because thou hast forgotten me, and trusted in falsehood. 
\v 26 Therefore will I discover thy skirts upon thy face, that thy shame may appear. 
\v 27 I have seen thine adulteries, and thy neighings, the lewdness of thy whoredom, \add and\add* thine abominations on the hills in the fields. Woe unto thee, O Jerusalem! wilt thou not be made clean? when \add shall it\add* once \add be?\add* 
\c 14  
\p
\v 1 The word of the \sc Lord\sc* that came to Jeremiah concerning the dearth. 
\q1
\v 2 Judah mourneth, and the gates thereof languish; 
\q1 They are black unto the ground; 
\q1 And the cry of Jerusalem is gone up. 
\q1
\v 3 And their nobles have sent their little ones to the waters: 
\q1 They came to the pits, \add and\add* found no water; 
\q1 They returned \add with\add* their vessels empty; 
\q1 They were ashamed and confounded, and covered their heads. 
\q1
\v 4 Because the ground is chapt, 
\q1 For there was no rain in the earth, 
\q1 The plowmen were ashamed, they covered their heads. 
\q1
\v 5 Yea, the hind also calved in the field, and forsook \add it\add*, 
\q1 Because there was no grass. 
\q1
\v 6 And the wild asses did stand in the high places, 
\q1 They snuffed up the wind like dragons; 
\q1 Their eyes did fail, because \add there was\add* no grass. 
\p
\v 7 O \sc Lord\sc*, though our iniquities testify against us, do thou \add it\add* for thy name’s sake: for our backslidings are many; we have sinned against thee. 
\v 8 O the hope of Israel, the saviour thereof in time of trouble, why shouldest thou be as a stranger in the land, and as a wayfaring man \add that\add* turneth aside to tarry for a night? 
\v 9 Why shouldest thou be as a man astonied, as a mighty \add man that\add* cannot save? yet thou, O \sc Lord\sc*, \add art\add* in the midst of us, and we are called by thy name; leave us not. 
\v 10 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* unto this people, Thus have they loved to wander, they have not refrained their feet, therefore the \sc Lord\sc* doth not accept them; he will now remember their iniquity, and visit their sins. 
\v 11 Then said the \sc Lord\sc* unto me, Pray not for this people for \add their\add* good. 
\v 12 When they fast, I will not hear their cry; and when they offer burnt offering and an oblation, I will not accept them: but I will consume them by the sword, and by the famine, and by the pestilence. 
\p
\v 13 Then said I, Ah Lord \sc God\sc*! behold, the prophets say unto them, Ye shall not see the sword, neither shall ye have famine; but I will give you assured peace in this place. 
\v 14 Then the \sc Lord\sc* said unto me, The prophets prophesy lies in my name: I sent them not, neither have I commanded them, neither spake unto them: they prophesy unto you a false vision and divination, and a thing of nought, and the deceit of their heart. 
\v 15 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* concerning the prophets that prophesy in my name, and I sent them not, yet they say, Sword and famine shall not be in this land; By sword and famine shall those prophets be consumed. 
\v 16 And the people to whom they prophesy shall be cast out in the streets of Jerusalem because of the famine and the sword; and they \add shall\add* have none to bury them, them, their wives, nor their sons, nor their daughters: for I will pour their wickedness upon them. 
\v 17 Therefore thou shalt say this word unto them; 
\q1 Let mine eyes run down \add with\add* tears night and day, and let them not cease: 
\q1 For the virgin daughter of my people is broken \add with\add* a great breach, \add with\add* a very grievous blow. 
\q1
\v 18 If I go forth \add into\add* the field, then behold the slain with the sword: 
\q1 And if I enter \add into\add* the city, then behold them that are sick with famine: 
\q1 Yea, both the prophet and the priest go about into a land that they know not. 
\q1
\v 19 Hast thou utterly rejected Judah? hath thy soul lothed Zion? 
\q1 Why hast thou smitten us, and \add there is\add* no healing for us? 
\q1 \add We\add* looked for peace, and \add there is\add* no good; 
\q1 And for the time of healing, and behold trouble. 
\q1
\v 20 We acknowledge, O \sc Lord\sc*, our wickedness, \add and\add* the iniquity of our fathers: 
\q1 For we have sinned against thee. 
\q1
\v 21 Do not abhor \add us\add*, for thy name’s sake, 
\q1 Do not disgrace the throne of thy glory: 
\q1 Remember, break not thy covenant with us. 
\q1
\v 22 Are there \add any\add* among the vanities of the Gentiles that can cause rain? 
\q1 Or can the heavens give showers? 
\q1 \add Art\add* not thou he, O \sc Lord\sc* our God? therefore we will wait upon thee: 
\q1 For thou hast made all these \add things\add*. 
\c 15  
\p
\v 1 Then said the \sc Lord\sc* unto me, Though Moses and Samuel stood before me, \add yet\add* my mind \add could\add* not \add be\add* toward this people: cast \add them\add* out of my sight, and let them go forth. 
\v 2 And it shall come to pass, if they say unto thee, Whither shall we go forth? then thou shalt tell them, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Such as \add are\add* for death, to death; and such as \add are\add* for the sword, to the sword; and such as \add are\add* for the famine, to the famine; and such as \add are\add* for the captivity, to the captivity. 
\v 3 And I will appoint over them four kinds, saith the \sc Lord\sc*: the sword to slay, and the dogs to tear, and the fowls of the heaven, and the beasts of the earth, to devour and destroy. 
\v 4 And I will cause them to be removed into all kingdoms of the earth, because of Manasseh the son of Hezekiah king of Judah, for \add that\add* which he did in Jerusalem. 
\v 5 For who shall have pity upon thee, O Jerusalem? or who shall bemoan thee? or who shall go aside to ask how thou doest? 
\v 6 Thou hast forsaken me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, thou art gone backward: therefore will I stretch out my hand against thee, and destroy thee; I am weary with repenting. 
\v 7 And I will fan them with a fan in the gates of the land; I will bereave \add them\add* of children, I will destroy my people, \add sith\add* they return not from their ways. 
\v 8 Their widows are increased to me above the sand of the seas: I have brought upon them against the mother of the young men a spoiler at noonday: I have caused \add him\add* to fall upon it suddenly, and terrors \add upon\add* the city. 
\v 9 She that hath borne seven languisheth: she hath given up the ghost; her sun is gone down while \add it was\add* yet day: she hath been ashamed and confounded: and the residue of them will I deliver to the sword before their enemies, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\p
\v 10 Woe is me, my mother, that thou hast borne me a man of strife and a man of contention to the whole earth! I have neither lent on usury, nor \add men\add* have lent to me on usury; \add yet\add* every one of them doth curse me. 
\v 11 The \sc Lord\sc* said, Verily it shall be well with thy remnant; verily I will cause the enemy to entreat thee \add well\add* in the time of evil, and in the time of affliction. 
\v 12 Shall iron break the northern iron and the steel? 
\v 13 Thy substance and thy treasures will I give to the spoil without price, and \add that\add* for all thy sins, even in all thy borders. 
\v 14 And I will make \add thee\add* to pass with thine enemies into a land \add which\add* thou knowest not: for a fire is kindled in mine anger, \add which\add* shall burn upon you. 
\p
\v 15 O \sc Lord\sc*, thou knowest: remember me, and visit me, and revenge me of my persecutors; take me not away in thy longsuffering: know that for thy sake I have suffered rebuke. 
\v 16 Thy words were found, and I did eat them; and thy word was unto me the joy and rejoicing of mine heart: for I am called by thy name, O \sc Lord\sc* God of hosts. 
\v 17 I sat not in the assembly of the mockers, nor rejoiced; I sat alone because of thy hand: for thou hast filled me \add with\add* indignation. 
\v 18 Why is my pain perpetual, and my wound incurable, \add which\add* refuseth to be healed? wilt thou be altogether unto me as a liar, \add and as\add* waters \add that\add* fail? 
\p
\v 19 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, If thou return, then will I bring thee again, \add and\add* thou shalt stand before me: and if thou take forth the precious from the vile, thou shalt be as my mouth: let them return unto thee; but return not thou unto them. 
\v 20 And I will make thee unto this people a fenced brasen wall: and they shall fight against thee, but they shall not prevail against thee: for I \add am\add* with thee to save thee and to deliver thee, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 21 And I will deliver thee out of the hand of the wicked, and I will redeem thee out of the hand of the terrible. 
\c 16  
\p
\v 1 The word of the \sc Lord\sc* came also unto me, saying, 
\v 2 Thou shalt not take thee a wife, neither shalt thou have sons nor daughters in this place. 
\v 3 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* concerning the sons and concerning the daughters that are born in this place, and concerning their mothers that bare them, and concerning their fathers that begat them in this land; 
\v 4 they shall die of grievous deaths; they shall not be lamented; neither shall they be buried; \add but\add* they shall be as dung upon the face of the earth: and they shall be consumed by the sword, and by famine; and their carcases shall be meat for the fowls of heaven, and for the beasts of the earth. 
\v 5 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, Enter not \add into\add* the house of mourning, neither go to lament nor bemoan them: for I have taken away my peace from this people, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, \add even\add* lovingkindness and mercies. 
\v 6 Both the great and the small shall die in this land: they shall not be buried, neither shall \add men\add* lament for them, nor cut themselves, nor make themselves bald for them: 
\v 7 neither shall \add men\add* tear \add themselves\add* for them in mourning, to comfort them for the dead; neither shall \add men\add* give them the cup of consolation to drink for their father or for their mother. 
\v 8 Thou shalt not also go \add into\add* the house of feasting, to sit with them to eat and to drink. 
\v 9 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, the God of Israel; Behold, I will cause to cease out of this place in your eyes, and in your days, the voice of mirth, and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride. 
\v 10 And it shall come to pass, when thou shalt shew this people all these words, and they shall say unto thee, Wherefore hath the \sc Lord\sc* pronounced all this great evil against us? or what \add is\add* our iniquity? or what \add is\add* our sin that we have committed against the \sc Lord\sc* our God? 
\v 11 Then shalt thou say unto them, Because your fathers have forsaken me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and have walked after other gods, and have served them, and have worshipped them, and have forsaken me, and have not kept my law; 
\v 12 and ye have done worse than your fathers; for behold, ye walk every one after the imagination of his evil heart, that \add they\add* may not hearken unto me: 
\v 13 therefore will I cast you out of this land into a land that ye know not, \add neither\add* ye nor your fathers; and there shall ye serve other gods day and night; where I will not shew you favour. 
\p
\v 14 Therefore behold, the days come, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that it shall no more be said, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth, that brought up the children of Israel out of the land of Egypt; 
\v 15 but, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth, that brought up the children of Israel from the land of the north, and from all the lands whither he had driven them: and I will bring them again into their land that I gave unto their fathers. 
\v 16 Behold, I will send for many fishers, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and they shall fish them; and after will I send for many hunters, and they shall hunt them from every mountain, and from every hill, and out of the holes of the rocks. 
\v 17 For mine eyes \add are\add* upon all their ways: they are not hid from my face, neither is their iniquity hid from mine eyes. 
\v 18 And first I will recompense their iniquity and their sin double; because they have defiled my land, they have filled mine inheritance with the carcases of their detestable and abominable things. 
\v 19 O \sc Lord\sc*, my strength, and my fortress, and my refuge in the day of affliction, the Gentiles shall come unto thee from the ends of the earth, and shall say, Surely our fathers have inherited lies, vanity, and \add things\add* wherein \add there is\add* no profit. 
\v 20 Shall a man make gods unto himself, and they \add are\add* no gods? 
\v 21 Therefore behold, I \add will\add* this once cause them to know, I will cause them to know mine hand and my might; and they shall know that my name \add is\add* The \sc Lord\sc*. 
\c 17  
\p
\v 1 The sin of Judah \add is\add* written with a pen of iron, \add and\add* with the point of a diamond: \add it is\add* graven upon the table of their heart, and upon the horns of your altars; 
\v 2 whilst their children remember their altars and their groves by the green trees upon the high hills. 
\v 3 O my mountain in the field, I will give thy substance \add and\add* all thy treasures to the spoil, \add and\add* thy high places for sin, throughout all thy borders. 
\v 4 And thou, even thyself, shalt discontinue from thine heritage that I gave thee; and I will cause thee to serve thine enemies in the land which thou knowest not: for ye have kindled a fire in mine anger, \add which\add* shall burn for ever. 
\p
\v 5 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Cursed \add be\add* the man that trusteth in man, and maketh flesh his arm, and whose heart departeth from the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 6 For he shall be like the heath in the desert, and shall not see when good cometh; but shall inhabit the parched places in the wilderness, \add in\add* a salt land and not inhabited. 
\v 7 Blessed \add is\add* the man that trusteth in the \sc Lord\sc*, and whose hope the \sc Lord\sc* is. 
\v 8 For he shall be as a tree planted by the waters, and \add that\add* spreadeth out her roots by the river, and shall not see when heat cometh, but her leaf shall be green; and shall not be careful in the year of drought, neither shall cease from yielding fruit. 
\p
\v 9 The heart \add is\add* deceitful above all \add things\add*, and desperately wicked: who can know it? 
\v 10 I the \sc Lord\sc* search the heart, \add I\add* try the reins, even to give every man according to his ways, \add and\add* according to the fruit of his doings. 
\v 11  \add As\add* the partridge sitteth \add on eggs\add*, and hatcheth \add them\add* not; \add so\add* he that getteth riches, and not by right, shall leave them in the midst of his days, and at his end shall be a fool. 
\p
\v 12 A glorious high throne from the beginning \add is\add* the place of our sanctuary. 
\v 13 O \sc Lord\sc*, the hope of Israel, all that forsake thee shall be ashamed, and they that depart from me shall be written in the earth, because they have forsaken the \sc Lord\sc*, the fountain of living waters. 
\v 14 Heal me, O \sc Lord\sc*, and I shall be healed; save me, and I shall be saved: for thou \add art\add* my praise. 
\v 15 Behold, they say unto me, Where \add is\add* the word of the \sc Lord\sc*? let it come now. 
\v 16 As for me, I have not hastened from \add being\add* a pastor to follow thee: neither have I desired the woeful day; thou knowest: that which came out of my lips was right before thee. 
\v 17 Be not a terror unto me: thou \add art\add* my hope in the day of evil. 
\v 18 Let them be confounded that persecute me, but let not me be confounded: let them be dismayed, but let not me be dismayed: bring upon them the day of evil, and destroy them \add with\add* double destruction. 
\p
\v 19 Thus said the \sc Lord\sc* unto me; Go and stand in the gate of the children of the people, whereby the kings of Judah come in, and by the which they go out, and in all the gates of Jerusalem; 
\v 20 and say unto them, Hear ye the word of the \sc Lord\sc*, ye kings of Judah, and all Judah, and all the inhabitants of Jerusalem, that enter in by these gates: 
\v 21 thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Take heed to yourselves, and bear no burden on the sabbath day, nor bring \add it\add* in by the gates of Jerusalem; 
\v 22 neither carry forth a burden out of your houses on the sabbath day, neither do ye any work, but hallow ye the sabbath day, as I commanded your fathers. 
\v 23 But they obeyed not, neither inclined their ear, but made their neck stiff, that \add they\add* might not hear, nor receive instruction. 
\v 24 And it shall come to pass, if ye diligently hearken unto me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, to bring in no burden through the gates of this city on the sabbath day, but hallow the sabbath day, to do no work therein; 
\v 25 then shall there enter into the gates of this city kings and princes sitting upon the throne of David, riding in chariots and on horses, they, and their princes, the men of Judah, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem: and this city shall remain for ever. 
\v 26 And they shall come from the cities of Judah, and from the places about Jerusalem, and from the land of Benjamin, and from the plain, and from the mountains, and from the south, bringing burnt offerings, and sacrifices, and meat offerings, and incense, and bringing \add sacrifices of\add* praise, \add unto\add* the house of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 27 But if you will not hearken unto me to hallow the sabbath day, and not to bear a burden, even entering in at the gates of Jerusalem on the sabbath day; then will I kindle a fire in the gates thereof, and it shall devour the palaces of Jerusalem, and it shall not be quenched. 
\c 18  
\p
\v 1 The word which came to Jeremiah from the \sc Lord\sc*, saying, 
\v 2 Arise, and go down \add to\add* the potter’s house, and there I will cause thee to hear my words. 
\v 3 Then I went down \add to\add* the potter’s house, and behold, he wrought a work on the wheels. 
\v 4 And the vessel that he made of clay was marred in the hand of the potter: so he made it again another vessel, as seemed good to the potter to make \add it\add*. 
\v 5 Then the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came to me, saying, 
\v 6 O house of Israel, cannot I do with you as this potter? saith the \sc Lord\sc*. Behold, as the clay \add is\add* in the potter’s hand, so \add are\add* ye in mine hand, O house of Israel. 
\v 7  \add At what\add* instant I shall speak concerning a nation and concerning a kingdom, to pluck up, and to pull down, and to destroy \add it;\add* 
\v 8 if that nation, against whom I have pronounced, turn from their evil, I will repent of the evil that I thought to do unto them. 
\v 9 And \add at what\add* instant I shall speak concerning a nation, and concerning a kingdom, to build and to plant \add it;\add* 
\v 10 if it do evil in my sight, that \add it\add* obey not my voice, then I will repent of the good, wherewith I said \add I\add* would benefit them. 
\v 11 Now therefore go to, speak to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, saying, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Behold, I frame evil against you, and devise a device against you: return ye now every one from his evil way, and make your ways and your doings good. 
\v 12 And they said, There is no hope: but we will walk after our own devices, and we will every one do the imagination of his evil heart. 
\v 13 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Ask ye now among the heathen, who hath heard such \add things:\add* the virgin of Israel hath done a very horrible thing. 
\v 14 Will \add a man\add* leave the snow of Lebanon \add which cometh\add* from the rock of the field? \add or\add* shall the cold flowing waters that come from another place be forsaken? 
\v 15 Because my people hath forgotten me, they have burnt incense to vanity, and they have caused them to stumble in their ways \add from\add* the ancient paths, to walk \add in\add* paths, \add in\add* a way not cast up; 
\v 16 to make their land desolate, \add and\add* a perpetual hissing; every one that passeth thereby shall be astonished, and wag his head. 
\v 17 I will scatter them as \add with\add* an east wind before the enemy; I will shew them the back, and not the face, in the day of their calamity. 
\p
\v 18 Then said they, Come, and let us devise devices against Jeremiah; for the law shall not perish from the priest, nor counsel from the wise, nor the word from the prophet. Come, and let us smite him with the tongue, and let us not give heed to any of his words. 
\v 19 Give heed to me, O \sc Lord\sc*, and hearken to the voice of them that contend with me. 
\v 20 Shall evil be recompensed for good? for they have digged a pit for my soul. Remember that I stood before thee to speak good for them, \add and\add* to turn away thy wrath from them. 
\v 21 Therefore deliver up their children to the famine, and pour out their \add blood\add* by the force of the sword; and let their wives be bereaved of their children, and \add be\add* widows; and let their men be put to death; \add let\add* their young men \add be\add* slain by the sword in battle. 
\v 22 Let a cry be heard from their houses, when thou shalt bring a troop suddenly upon them: for they have digged a pit to take me, and hid snares for my feet. 
\v 23 Yet, \sc Lord\sc*, thou knowest all their counsel against me to slay \add me:\add* forgive not their iniquity, neither blot out their sin from thy sight, but let them be overthrown before thee; deal \add thus\add* with them in the time of thine anger. 
\c 19  
\p
\v 1 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, Go and get a potter’s earthen bottle, and \add take\add* of the ancients of the people, and of the ancients of the priests; 
\v 2 and go forth unto the valley of the son of Hinnom, which \add is by\add* the entry of the east gate, and proclaim there the words that I shall tell thee, 
\v 3 and say, Hear ye the word of the \sc Lord\sc*, O kings of Judah, and inhabitants of Jerusalem; Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, the God of Israel; Behold, I \add will\add* bring evil upon this place, the which whosoever heareth, his ears shall tingle. 
\v 4 Because they have forsaken me, and have estranged this place, and have burnt incense in it unto other gods, whom neither they nor their fathers have known, nor the kings of Judah, and have filled this place \add with\add* the blood of innocents; 
\v 5 they have built also the high places of Baal, to burn their sons with fire \add for\add* burnt offerings unto Baal, which I commanded not, nor spake \add it\add*, neither came \add it\add* into my mind: 
\v 6 therefore behold, the days come, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that this place shall no more be called Tophet, nor The valley of the son of Hinnom, but The valley of slaughter. 
\v 7 And I will make void the counsel of Judah and Jerusalem in this place; and I will cause them to fall by the sword before their enemies, and by the hands of them that seek their lives: and their carcases will I give to be meat for the fowls of the heaven, and for the beasts of the earth. 
\v 8 And I will make this city desolate, and a hissing; every one that passeth thereby shall be astonished and hiss because of all the plagues thereof. 
\v 9 And I will cause them to eat the flesh of their sons and the flesh of their daughters, and they shall eat every one the flesh of his friend in the siege and straitness, wherewith their enemies, and they that seek their lives, shall straiten them. 
\v 10 Then shalt thou break the bottle in the sight of the men that go with thee, 
\v 11 and shalt say unto them, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts; Even so will I break this people and this city, as \add one\add* breaketh a potter’s vessel, that cannot be made whole again: and they shall bury \add them\add* in Tophet, till \add there be\add* no place to bury. 
\v 12 Thus will I do unto this place, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and to the inhabitants thereof, and \add even\add* make this city as Tophet: 
\v 13 And the houses of Jerusalem, and the houses of the kings of Judah, shall be defiled as the place of Tophet, because of all the houses upon whose roofs they have burnt incense unto all the host of heaven, and have poured out drink offerings unto other gods. 
\p
\v 14 Then came Jeremiah from Tophet, whither the \sc Lord\sc* had sent him to prophesy; and he stood in the court of the \sc Lord’s\sc* house; and said to all the people, 
\v 15 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, the God of Israel; Behold, I will bring upon this city and upon all her towns all the evil that I have pronounced against it, because they have hardened their necks, that \add they\add* might not hear my words. 
\c 20  
\nb
\v 1 Now Pashur the son of Immer the priest, who \add was\add* also chief governor in the house of the \sc Lord\sc*, heard \add that\add* Jeremiah prophesied these things. 
\v 2 Then Pashur smote Jeremiah the prophet, and put him in the stocks that \add were\add* in the high gate of Benjamin, which \add was\add* by the house of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 3 And it came to pass on the morrow, that Pashur brought forth Jeremiah out of the stocks. Then said Jeremiah unto him, The \sc Lord\sc* hath not called thy name Pashur, but Magor-missabib. 
\v 4 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, Behold, I will make thee a terror to thyself, and to all thy friends: and they shall fall by the sword of their enemies, and thine eyes \add shall\add* behold \add it;\add* and I will give all Judah into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he shall carry them captive into Babylon, and shall slay them with the sword. 
\v 5 Moreover I will deliver all the strength of this city, and all the labours thereof, and all the precious things thereof, and all the treasures of the kings of Judah will I give into the hand of their enemies, which shall spoil them, and take them, and carry them to Babylon. 
\v 6 And thou, Pashur, and all that dwell in thine house shall go into captivity: and thou shalt come \add to\add* Babylon, and there thou shalt die, and shalt be buried there, thou, and all thy friends, to whom thou hast prophesied lies. 
\q1
\v 7 O \sc Lord\sc*, thou hast deceived me, and I was deceived: 
\q1 Thou art stronger than I, and hast prevailed: 
\q1 I am in derision daily, 
\q1 Every one mocketh me. 
\q1
\v 8 For since I spake, I cried out, 
\q1 I cried violence and spoil; 
\q1 Because the word of the \sc Lord\sc* was made a reproach unto me, 
\q1 And a derision, daily. 
\q1
\v 9 Then I said, I will not make mention of him, 
\q1 Nor speak any more in his name. 
\q1 But \add his word\add* was in mine heart as a burning fire shut up in my bones, 
\q1 And I was weary with forbearing, and I could not stay. 
\q1
\v 10 For I heard the defaming of many, fear on every side. 
\q1 Report, \add say they\add*, and we will report it. 
\q1 All my familiars watched for my halting, \add saying\add*, 
\q1 Peradventure he will be enticed, and we shall prevail against him, 
\q1 And we shall take our revenge on him. 
\q1
\v 11 But the \sc Lord\sc* \add is\add* with me as a mighty terrible one: 
\q1 Therefore my persecutors shall stumble, and they shall not prevail: 
\q1 They shall be greatly ashamed: for they shall not prosper: 
\q1 \add Their\add* everlasting confusion shall never be forgotten. 
\q1
\v 12 But, O \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, that triest the righteous, 
\q1 \add And\add* seest the reins and the heart, 
\q1 Let me see thy vengeance on them: 
\q1 For unto thee have I opened my cause. 
\q1
\v 13 Sing unto the \sc Lord\sc*, praise ye the \sc Lord\sc*: 
\q1 For he hath delivered the soul of the poor from the hand of evildoers. 
\b
\q1
\v 14 Cursed \add be\add* the day wherein I was born: 
\q1 Let not the day wherein my mother bare me be blessed. 
\q1
\v 15 Cursed \add be\add* the man who brought tidings to my father, saying, 
\q1 A man child is born unto thee; 
\q1 Making him very glad. 
\q1
\v 16 And let that man be as the cities which the \sc Lord\sc* overthrew, and repented not: 
\q1 And let him hear the cry in the morning, and the shouting at noontide; 
\q1
\v 17 Because he slew me not from the womb; 
\q1 Or that my mother might have been my grave, 
\q1 And her womb \add to be\add* always great \add with me\add*. 
\q1
\v 18 Wherefore came I forth out of the womb 
\q1 To see labour and sorrow, 
\q1 That my days should be consumed with shame? 
\c 21  
\p
\v 1 The word which came unto Jeremiah from the \sc Lord\sc*, when king Zedekiah sent unto him Pashur the son of Melchiah, and Zephaniah the son of Maaseiah the priest, saying, 
\v 2 Inquire, I pray thee, of the \sc Lord\sc* for us; for Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon maketh war against us; if so be that the \sc Lord\sc* will deal with us according to all his wondrous works, that he may go up from us. 
\v 3 Then said Jeremiah unto them, Thus shall ye say to Zedekiah: 
\v 4 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* God of Israel; Behold, I \add will\add* turn back the weapons of war that \add are\add* in your hands, wherewith ye fight against the king of Babylon, and against the Chaldeans, which besiege you without the walls, and I will assemble them into the midst of this city. 
\v 5 And I myself will fight against you with an outstretched hand and with a strong arm, even in anger, and in fury, and in great wrath. 
\v 6 And I will smite the inhabitants of this city, both man and beast: they shall die of a great pestilence. 
\v 7 And afterward, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, I will deliver Zedekiah king of Judah, and his servants, and the people, and such as are left in this city from the pestilence, from the sword, and from the famine, into the hand of Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon, and into the hand of their enemies, and into the hand of those that seek their life: and he shall smite them with the edge of the sword; he shall not spare them, neither have pity, nor have mercy. 
\p
\v 8 And unto this people thou shalt say, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Behold, I set before you the way of life, and the way of death. 
\v 9 He that abideth in this city shall die by the sword, and by the famine, and by the pestilence: but he that goeth out, and falleth to the Chaldeans that besiege you, he shall live, and his life shall be unto him for a prey. 
\v 10 For I have set my face against this city for evil, and not for good, saith the \sc Lord\sc*: it shall be given into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he shall burn it with fire. 
\v 11 And touching the house of the king of Judah, \add say\add*, Hear ye the word of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 12 O house of David, thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Execute judgment in the morning, and deliver \add him that is\add* spoiled out of the hand of the oppressor, lest my fury go out like fire, and burn that none can quench \add it\add*, because of the evil of your doings. 
\v 13 Behold, I \add am\add* against thee, O inhabitant of the valley, \add and\add* rock of the plain, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; which say, Who shall come down against us? or who shall enter into our habitations? 
\v 14 But I will punish you according to the fruit of your doings, saith the \sc Lord\sc*: and I will kindle a fire in the forest thereof, and it shall devour all things round about it. 
\c 22  
\p
\v 1 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Go down \add to\add* the house of the king of Judah, and speak there this word, 
\v 2 and say, Hear the word of the \sc Lord\sc*, O king of Judah, that sittest upon the throne of David, thou, and thy servants, and thy people that enter in by these gates: 
\v 3 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Execute ye judgment and righteousness, and deliver the spoiled out of the hand of the oppressor; and do no wrong, do no violence, to the stranger, the fatherless, nor the widow, neither shed innocent blood in this place. 
\v 4 For if ye do this thing indeed, then shall there enter in by the gates of this house kings sitting upon the throne of David, riding in chariots and on horses, he, and his servants, and his people. 
\v 5 But if ye will not hear these words, I swear by myself, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that this house shall become a desolation. 
\v 6 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* unto the king’s house of Judah; Thou \add art\add* Gilead unto me, \add and\add* the head of Lebanon: \add yet\add* surely I will make thee a wilderness \add and\add* cities \add which\add* are not inhabited. 
\v 7 And I will prepare destroyers against thee, every one with his weapons: and they shall cut down thy choice cedars, and cast \add them\add* into the fire. 
\v 8 And many nations shall pass by this city, and they shall say every man to his neighbour, Wherefore hath the \sc Lord\sc* done thus unto this great city? 
\v 9 Then they shall answer, Because they have forsaken the covenant of the \sc Lord\sc* their God, and worshipped other gods, and served them. 
\q1
\v 10 Weep ye not for the dead, neither bemoan him: 
\q1 \add But\add* weep sore for him that goeth away: 
\q1 For he shall return no more, 
\q1 Nor see his native country. 
\p
\v 11 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* touching Shallum the son of Josiah king of Judah, which reigned instead of Josiah his father, which went forth out of this place; He shall not return thither any more: 
\v 12 but he shall die in the place whither they have led him captive, and shall see this land no more. 
\q1
\v 13 Woe unto him that buildeth his house by unrighteousness, 
\q1 And his chambers by wrong; 
\q1 \add That\add* useth his neighbour’s service without wages, 
\q1 And giveth him not \add for\add* his work; 
\q1
\v 14 That saith, I will build me a wide house and large chambers, 
\q1 And cutteth him out windows; 
\q1 And \add it is\add* cieled with cedar, and painted with vermilion. 
\q1
\v 15 Shalt thou reign, because thou closest \add thyself\add* in cedar? 
\q1 Did not thy father eat and drink, 
\q1 And do judgment and justice, 
\q1 \add And\add* then \add it was\add* well with him? 
\q1
\v 16 He judged the cause of the poor and needy; then \add it was\add* well \add with him:\add* 
\q1 \add Was\add* not this to know me? saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\q1
\v 17 But thine eyes and thine heart \add are\add* not but for thy covetousness, 
\q1 And for to shed innocent blood, 
\q1 And for oppression, and for violence, to do \add it\add*. 
\q1
\v 18 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* concerning Jehoiakim the son of Josiah king of Judah; 
\q1 They shall not lament for him, \add saying\add*, Ah my brother! or, Ah sister! 
\q1 They shall not lament for him, \add saying\add*, Ah lord! or, Ah his glory. 
\q1
\v 19 He shall be buried \add with\add* the burial of an ass, 
\q1 Drawn and cast forth beyond the gates of Jerusalem. 
\q1
\v 20 Go up \add to\add* Lebanon, and cry; and lift up thy voice in Bashan, 
\q1 And cry from the passages: 
\q1 For all thy lovers are destroyed. 
\q1
\v 21 I spake unto thee in thy prosperity; 
\q1 \add But\add* thou saidst, I will not hear. 
\q1 This \add hath been\add* thy manner from thy youth, 
\q1 That thou obeyedst not my voice. 
\q1
\v 22 The wind shall eat up all thy pastors, 
\q1 And thy lovers shall go into captivity: 
\q1 Surely then shalt thou be ashamed and confounded for all thy wickedness. 
\q1
\v 23 O inhabitant of Lebanon, that makest thy nest in the cedars, 
\q1 How gracious shalt thou be when pangs come upon thee, 
\q1 The pain as of a woman in travail. 
\p
\v 24  \add As\add* I live, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, though Coniah the son of Jehoiakim king of Judah were the signet upon my right hand, yet would I pluck thee thence; 
\v 25 and I will give thee into the hand of them that seek thy life, and into the hand \add of them\add* whose face thou fearest, even into the hand of Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon, and into the hand of the Chaldeans. 
\v 26 And I will cast thee out, and thy mother that bare thee, into another country, where ye were not born; and there shall ye die. 
\v 27 But to the land whereunto they desire to return, thither shall they not return. 
\v 28  \add Is\add* this man Coniah a despised broken idol? \add is he\add* a vessel wherein \add is\add* no pleasure? wherefore are they cast out, he and his seed, and are cast into a land which they know not? 
\v 29 O earth, earth, earth, hear the word of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 30 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, Write ye this man childless, a man \add that\add* shall not prosper in his days: for no man of his seed shall prosper, sitting upon the throne of David, and ruling any more in Judah. 
\c 23  
\p
\v 1 Woe be unto \add the\add* pastors that destroy and scatter the sheep of my pasture! saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 2 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* God of Israel against the pastors that feed my people; Ye have scattered my flock, and driven them away, and have not visited them: behold, I will visit upon you the evil of your doings, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 3 And I will gather the remnant of my flock out of all countries whither I have driven them, and will bring them again to their folds; and they shall be fruitful and increase. 
\v 4 And I will set up shepherds over them which shall feed them: and they shall fear no more, nor be dismayed, neither shall they be lacking, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\p
\v 5 Behold, the days come, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that I will raise unto David a righteous Branch, and a King shall reign and prosper, and shall execute judgment and justice in the earth. 
\v 6 In his days Judah shall be saved, and Israel shall dwell safely: and this \add is\add* his name whereby he shall be called, THE LORD OUR RIGHTEOUSNESS. 
\v 7 Therefore behold, the days come, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that they shall no more say, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth, which brought up the children of Israel out of the land of Egypt; 
\v 8 but, The \sc Lord\sc* liveth, which brought up and which led the seed of the house of Israel out of the north country, and from all countries whither I had driven them; and they shall dwell in their own land. 
\q1
\v 9 Mine heart within me is broken because of the prophets; 
\q1 All my bones shake; 
\q1 I am like a drunken man, 
\q1 And like a man whom wine hath overcome, 
\q1 Because of the \sc Lord\sc*, and because of the words of his holiness. 
\q1
\v 10 For the land is full \add of\add* adulterers; 
\q1 For because of swearing the land mourneth; 
\q1 The pleasant places of the wilderness are dried up, 
\q1 And their course is evil, and their force \add is\add* not right. 
\q1
\v 11 For both prophet and priest are profane; 
\q1 Yea, in my house have I found their wickedness, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\q1
\v 12 Wherefore their way shall be unto them as slippery \add ways\add* in the darkness: 
\q1 They shall be driven on, and fall therein: 
\q1 For I will bring evil upon them, \add even\add* the year of their visitation, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\q1
\v 13 And I have seen folly in the prophets of Samaria; 
\q1 They prophesied in Baal, 
\q1 And caused my people Israel to err. 
\q1
\v 14 I have seen also in the prophets of Jerusalem a horrible thing: 
\q1 \add They\add* commit adultery, and walk in lies: 
\q1 They strengthen also the hands of evildoers, 
\q1 That none doth return from his wickedness: 
\q1 They are all of them unto me as Sodom, 
\q1 And the inhabitants thereof as Gomorrah. 
\p
\v 15 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts concerning the prophets; Behold, I will feed them with wormwood, and make them drink the water of gall: for from the prophets of Jerusalem is profaneness gone forth into all the land. 
\v 16 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, Hearken not unto the words of the prophets that prophesy unto you: they make you vain: they speak a vision of their own heart, \add and\add* not out of the mouth of the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 17 They say still unto them that despise me, The \sc Lord\sc* hath said, Ye shall have peace; and they say \add unto\add* every one that walketh after the imagination of his own heart, No evil shall come upon you. 
\v 18 For who hath stood in the counsel of the \sc Lord\sc*, and hath perceived and heard his word? who hath marked his word, and heard \add it?\add* 
\v 19 Behold, a whirlwind of the \sc Lord\sc* is gone forth \add in\add* fury, even a grievous whirlwind: it shall fall grievously upon the head of the wicked. 
\v 20 The anger of the \sc Lord\sc* shall not return, until he have executed, and till he have performed the thoughts of his heart: in the latter days ye shall consider it perfectly. 
\v 21 I have not sent \add these\add* prophets, yet they ran: I have not spoken to them, yet they prophesied. 
\v 22 But if they had stood in my counsel, and had caused my people to hear my words, then they should have turned them from their evil way, and from the evil of their doings. 
\v 23  \add Am\add* I a God at hand, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and not a God afar off? 
\v 24 Can any hide himself in secret places that I shall not see him? saith the \sc Lord\sc*. Do not I fill heaven and earth? saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 25 I have heard what the prophets said, that prophesy lies in my name, saying, I have dreamed, I have dreamed. 
\v 26 How long shall \add this\add* be in the heart of the prophets that prophesy lies? yea, \add they are\add* prophets of the deceit of their own heart; 
\v 27 which think to cause my people to forget my name by their dreams which they tell every man to his neighbour, as their fathers have forgotten my name for Baal. 
\v 28 The prophet that hath a dream, let him tell a dream; and he that hath my word, let him speak my word faithfully. What \add is\add* the chaff to the wheat? saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 29  \add Is\add* not my word like as a fire? saith the \sc Lord\sc*; and like a hammer \add that\add* breaketh the rock in pieces? 
\v 30 Therefore behold, I \add am\add* against the prophets, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that steal my words every one from his neighbour. 
\v 31 Behold, I \add am\add* against the prophets, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, that use their tongues, and say, He saith. 
\v 32 Behold, I \add am\add* against them that prophesy false dreams, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and do tell them, and cause my people to err by their lies, and by their lightness; yet I sent them not, nor commanded them: therefore they shall not profit this people at all, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\p
\v 33 And when this people, or the prophet, or a priest, shall ask thee, saying, What \add is\add* the burden of the \sc Lord\sc*? thou shalt then say unto them, What burden? I will even forsake you, saith the \sc Lord\sc*. 
\v 34 And \add as for\add* the prophet, and the priest, and the people, that shall say, The burden of the \sc Lord\sc*, I will even punish that man and his house. 
\v 35 Thus shall ye say every one to his neighbour, and every one to his brother, What hath the \sc Lord\sc* answered? and, What hath the \sc Lord\sc* spoken? 
\v 36 And the burden of the \sc Lord\sc* shall ye mention no more: for every man’s word shall be his burden; for ye have perverted the words of the living God, of the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts our God. 
\v 37 Thus shalt thou say to the prophet, What hath the \sc Lord\sc* answered thee? and, What hath the \sc Lord\sc* spoken? 
\v 38 But sith ye say, The burden of the \sc Lord\sc*; therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*; Because you say this word, The burden of the \sc Lord\sc*, and I have sent unto you, saying, Ye shall not say, The burden of the \sc Lord\sc*; 
\v 39 therefore behold, I, even I, will utterly forget you, and I will forsake you, and the city that I gave you and your fathers, \add and cast you\add* out of my presence: 
\v 40 and I will bring an everlasting reproach upon you, and a perpetual shame, which shall not be forgotten. 
\c 24  
\p
\v 1 The \sc Lord\sc* shewed me, and behold, two baskets of figs \add were\add* set before the temple of the \sc Lord\sc*, after that Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon had carried away captive Jeconiah the son of Jehoiakim king of Judah, and the princes of Judah, with the carpenters and smiths, from Jerusalem, and had brought them \add to\add* Babylon. 
\v 2 One basket \add had\add* very good figs, \add even\add* like the figs \add that are\add* first ripe: and the other basket \add had\add* very naughty figs, which could not be eaten, they were so bad. 
\v 3 Then said the \sc Lord\sc* unto me, What seest thou, Jeremiah? And I said, Figs; the good figs, very good; and the evil, very evil, that cannot be eaten, they are so evil. 
\v 4 Again the word of the \sc Lord\sc* came unto me, saying, 
\v 5 Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, the God of Israel; Like these good figs, so will I acknowledge them that are carried away captive of Judah, whom I have sent out of this place \add into\add* the land of the Chaldeans for \add their\add* good. 
\v 6 For I will set mine eyes upon them for good, and I will bring them again to this land: and I will build them, and not pull \add them\add* down; and I will plant them, and not pluck \add them\add* up. 
\v 7 And I will give them a heart to know me, that I \add am\add* the \sc Lord\sc*: and they shall be my people, and I will be their God: for they shall return unto me with their whole heart. 
\v 8 And as the evil figs, which cannot be eaten, they are so evil; surely thus saith the \sc Lord\sc*, So will I give Zedekiah the king of Judah, and his princes, and the residue of Jerusalem, that remain in this land, and them that dwell in the land of Egypt: 
\v 9 and I will deliver them to be removed into all the kingdoms of the earth for \add their\add* hurt, to be a reproach and a proverb, a taunt and a curse, in all places whither I shall drive them. 
\v 10 And I will send the sword, the famine, and the pestilence, among them, till they be consumed from off the land that I gave unto them and to their fathers. 
\c 25  
\p
\v 1 The word that came to Jeremiah concerning all the people of Judah in the fourth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah king of Judah, that \add was\add* the first year of Nebuchadrezzar king of Babylon; 
\v 2 the which Jeremiah the prophet spake unto all the people of Judah, and to all the inhabitants of Jerusalem, saying, 
\v 3 From the thirteenth year of Josiah the son of Amon king of Judah, even unto this day, that \add is\add* the three and twentieth year, the word of the \sc Lord\sc* hath come unto me, and I have spoken unto you, rising early and speaking; but ye have not hearkened. 
\v 4 And the \sc Lord\sc* hath sent unto you all his servants the prophets, rising early and sending \add them;\add* but ye have not hearkened, nor inclined your ear to hear. 
\v 5  \add They\add* said, Turn ye again now every one from his evil way, and from the evil of your doings, and dwell in the land that the \sc Lord\sc* hath given unto you and to your fathers for ever and ever: 
\v 6 and go not after other gods to serve them, and to worship them, and provoke me not to anger with the works of your hands; and I will do you no hurt. 
\v 7 Yet ye have not hearkened unto me, saith the \sc Lord\sc*; that \add ye\add* might provoke me to anger with the works of your hands to your own hurt. 
\p
\v 8 Therefore thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts; Because ye have not heard my words, 
\v 9 behold, I will send and take all the families of the north, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, and Nebuchadrezzar the king of Babylon, my servant, and will bring them against this land, and against the inhabitants thereof, and against all these nations round about, and will utterly destroy them, and make them an astonishment, and a hissing, and perpetual desolations. 
\v 10 Moreover I will take from them the voice of mirth, and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride, the sound of the millstones, and the light of the candle. 
\v 11 And this whole land shall be a desolation, \add and\add* an astonishment; and these nations shall serve the king of Babylon seventy years. 
\v 12 And it shall come to pass, when seventy years are accomplished, \add that\add* I will punish the king of Babylon, and that nation, saith the \sc Lord\sc*, for their iniquity, and the land of the Chaldeans, and will make it perpetual desolations. 
\v 13 And I will bring upon that land all my words which I have pronounced against it, \add even\add* all that is written in this book, which Jeremiah hath prophesied against all the nations. 
\v 14 For many nations and great kings shall serve themselves of them also: and I will recompense them according to their deeds, and according to the works of their own hands. 
\p
\v 15 For thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* God of Israel unto me; Take the wine cup of this fury at mine hand, and cause all the nations, to whom I send thee, to drink it. 
\v 16 And they shall drink, and be moved, and be mad, because of the sword that I will send among them. 
\v 17 Then took I the cup at the \sc Lord’s\sc* hand, and made all the nations to drink, unto whom the \sc Lord\sc* had sent me: 
\v 18  \add to wit\add*, Jerusalem, and the cities of Judah, and the kings thereof, \add and\add* the princes thereof, to make them a desolation, an astonishment, a hissing, and a curse; as \add it is\add* this day; 
\v 19 Pharaoh king of Egypt, and his servants, and his princes, and all his people; 
\v 20 and all the mingled people, and all the kings of the land of Uz, and all the kings of the land of the Philistines, and Ashkelon, and Azzah, and Ekron, and the remnant of Ashdod: 
\v 21 Edom, and Moab, and the children of Ammon, 
\v 22 and all the kings of Tyrus, and all the kings of Zidon, and the kings of the isles which \add are\add* beyond the sea, 
\v 23 Dedan, and Tema, and Buz, and all \add that are\add* in the utmost corners, 
\v 24 and all the kings of Arabia, and all the kings of the mingled people that dwell in the desert, 
\v 25 and all the kings of Zimri, and all the kings of Elam, and all the kings of the Medes, 
\v 26 and all the kings of the north, far and near, one with another, and all the kingdoms of the world, which \add are\add* upon the face of the earth: and the king of Sheshach shall drink after them. 
\v 27 Therefore thou shalt say unto them, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts, the God of Israel; Drink ye, and be drunken, and spue, and fall, and rise no more, because of the sword which I will send among you. 
\v 28 And it shall be, if they refuse to take the cup at thine hand to drink, then shalt thou say unto them, Thus saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts; Ye shall certainly drink. 
\v 29 For lo, I begin to bring evil on the city which is called by my name, and should ye be utterly unpunished? Ye shall not be unpunished: for I \add will\add* call for a sword upon all the inhabitants of the earth, saith the \sc Lord\sc* of hosts. 
\v 30 Therefore prophesy thou against them all these words, and say unto them, 
